  "articleSummary": "The article argues that multiple-choice questions (MCQs) are underutilized as teaching tools, not just assessment instruments. Its core thesis is that well-crafted wrong answers (distractors) representing real misconceptions can teach and diagnose mental models across expertise levels, as illustrated with a PostgreSQL identity column example. The tone is reflective and analytical, blending personal experience with instructional design insight, and uses recurring metaphors like \"the distractor is the curriculum\" and \"sorting mental models.\" Key points include that writing strong MCQs forces instructional precision and that the feedback loop benefits both author and learner. The intended audience is technical writers, educators, and programmers creating learning content.",
